CAPSTONE PROJECT PROBLEM STATEMENT

You have been appointed as the Lead Data Analyst to build a predictive model to determine if a building will have an insurance claim during a certain period or not. You will have to predict the probability of having at least one claim over the insured period of the building. The model will be based on the building characteristics.

The target variable, Claim, is a: 1 if the building has at least a claim over the insured period.0 if the building doesnt have a claim over the insured period.

You have the data description and the training data too Ensure you do all the necessary data preprocessing to improve your result, and evaluate too Also, your work should be added as a project to your GitHub repository.

The link to the repository that has your notebook(s) is what is expected to be submitted.

TO BE NOTED A good project contains

  1. A good data cleaning and preprocessing
  2. A detailed and explained set of insights through Exploratory Data Analysis
  3. A well-experimented preprocessing for modelling
  4. Implement more than 1 model
  5. Evaluate the models
No Variable Description
1 Customer Id Identification number for the Policy holder
2 YearOfObservation year of observation for the insured policy
3 Insured_Period duration of insurance policy in Olusola Insurance.
(Ex: Full year insurance, Policy Duration =1; 6 months = 0.5
4 Residential is the building a residential building or not
5 Building_Painted is the building painted or not (N-Painted, V-Not Painted)
6 Building_Fenced is the building fence or not (N-Fenced, V-Not Fenced)
7 Garden building has garden or not (V-has garden; O-no garden)
8 Settlement Area where the building is located. (R- rural area; U- urban area)
9 Building Dimension Size of the insured building in m2
10 Building_Type The type of building (Type 1, 2, 3, 4)
11 Date_of_Occupancy date building was first occupied
12 NumberOfWindows number of windows in the building
13 Geo Code Geographical Code of the Insured building
14 Claim target variable. (0: no claim, 1: at least one claim over insured period).

Objective: Predict the probability that a building will experience at least one insurance claim during the insured period using building characteristics.

Target Variable:

Claim = 1: At least one claim

Claim = 0: No claim

#The change persisted without inplace=True.

Decision Logic Missing values in numerical variables were imputed using the median to mitigate the impact of skewness and outliers. Categorical variables were imputed using the mode. Assignment-based imputation was used to avoid chained assignment and ensure compatibility with future versions of pandas.

THEREFORE; Assignment-based transformations were used instead of inplace operations to ensure explicit, permanent updates and compatibility with future pandas versions.

    'Insured_Period',
    'Building Dimension',
    'NumberOfWindows',
    'Building_Age'
]

for col in num_cols:
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))
    
    # Histogram
    sns.histplot(df[col], bins=30, kde=True, ax=axes[0])
    axes[0].set_title(f'Distribution of {col}')
    
    # Boxplot
    sns.boxplot(x=df[col], ax=axes[1])
    axes[1].set_title(f'Boxplot of {col}')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Analysis of the First Image

The first image displays three pairs of plots, each showing the distribution (histogram with Kernel Density Estimate) and a boxplot for a specific variable: Insured_Period, Building Dimension, and NumberOfWindows.

1. Insured_Period

  • Distribution of Insured_Period (Top Left Plot):
    • The distribution is extremely right-skewed, with a very strong peak at 1.0.
    • A vast majority of the data points for Insured_Period are concentrated at 1.0.
    • There's a long tail extending from 0.0 to 1.0, indicating a smaller number of instances with Insured_Period values less than 1.0.
    • The count at 1.0 is close to 6000, while other values have significantly lower counts.
  • Boxplot of Insured_Period (Top Right Plot):
    • The boxplot confirms the highly concentrated data. The box (representing the interquartile range, IQR) is extremely narrow and located at 1.0.
    • The median is also at 1.0.
    • The whiskers are very short, indicating little spread for the bulk of the data.
    • There are numerous individual data points (outliers) scattered between 0.0 and 1.0, which correspond to the long tail observed in the histogram. This suggests that while most policies cover a full period (perhaps a year, represented by 1.0), some cover shorter durations.

2. Building Dimension

  • Distribution of Building Dimension (Middle Left Plot):
    • The distribution is heavily right-skewed.
    • The highest frequency is for Building Dimension values close to 0 (or a very small positive number), peaking around 2500 counts.
    • The frequency rapidly decreases as Building Dimension increases.
    • The data ranges from 0 up to approximately 20000, with very few instances at the higher end.
  • Boxplot of Building Dimension (Middle Right Plot):

#To Define a Business-Oriented Confusion Matrix Function
#This enables the test of any threshold cleanly.
def evaluate_threshold(y_true, probs, threshold):
    preds = (probs >= threshold).astype(int)
    
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, preds)
    report = classification_report(y_true, preds, digits=3)
    
    return cm, report

#VISUAL CONFUSION MATRIX 

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(5,4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues',
                xticklabels=['No Claim', 'Claim'],
                yticklabels=['No Claim', 'Claim'])
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

plot_confusion_matrix(cm_05, 'Confusion Matrix  Threshold 0.5')
plot_confusion_matrix(cm_03, 'Confusion Matrix  Threshold 0.3')

DETAILED OBSERVATIONAL INTERPRETATION##

This image displays a "Precision-Recall vs Threshold" plot, which is a common visualization used in machine learning to evaluate the performance of a binary classifier.

Here's a detailed analysis:

  1. Plot Title and Axes:

    • Title: "Precision-Recall vs Threshold" clearly indicates what the plot represents.
    • X-axis: Labeled "Threshold," ranging from approximately 0.0 to 0.8. The threshold is a decision boundary used by the classifier; predictions above this value are typically classified as positive, and below as negative.
    • Y-axis: Labeled "Score," ranging from 0.0 to 1.0. This axis represents the values of both Precision and Recall.

  2. Curves:

    • Recall (Blue Line): This curve generally starts high (close to 1.0) at very low thresholds and steadily decreases as the threshold increases.
      • Interpretation: A low threshold means the model is more lenient in classifying instances as positive, leading to a higher number of true positives and thus higher recall (fewer false negatives). As the threshold increases, the model becomes stricter, leading to fewer true positives and more false negatives, hence lower recall.
    • Precision (Orange Line): This curve starts relatively low (around 0.2) at low thresholds, then generally increases as the threshold increases, reaching a peak around 0.7-0.8, and then shows some fluctuations, including a sharp drop and rise at higher thresholds (around 0.75-0.8).
      • Interpretation: A low threshold, while maximizing recall, often leads to many false positives, thus lowering precision. As the threshold increases, the model becomes more confident in its positive predictions, reducing false positives and generally increasing precision. The fluctuations at higher thresholds might indicate a sparse number of positive predictions, making the precision metric more sensitive to individual correct/incorrect classifications.

  3. Threshold Lines: The plot includes two vertical dashed lines indicating specific threshold values:

    • Threshold = 0.3 (Red Dashed Line):
      • At this threshold, the Recall (blue line) is approximately 0.45-0.5.
      • The Precision (orange line) is approximately 0.45-0.5.
      • At this point, Precision and Recall are roughly equal, indicating a balanced performance for these two metrics.
    • Threshold = 0.5 (Black Dashed Line):
      • At this threshold, the Recall (blue line) is approximately 0.15-0.2.
      • The Precision (orange line) is approximately 0.6-0.65.
      • Here, Precision is significantly higher than Recall. This threshold prioritizes making fewer false positive errors over finding all positive instances.

  4. Precision-Recall Trade-off: The plot clearly illustrates the inherent trade-off between precision and recall.

    • As the threshold decreases, recall tends to increase, but precision tends to decrease.
    • As the threshold increases, precision tends to increase (up to a point), but recall tends to decrease.
    • The optimal threshold depends on the specific application. If minimizing false negatives (finding all positive cases) is critical, a lower threshold (prioritizing recall) might be chosen. If minimizing false positives (ensuring positive predictions are highly accurate) is critical, a higher threshold (prioritizing precision) might be preferred.

In summary, this plot helps in selecting an appropriate classification threshold based on the desired balance between precision and recall for a given machine learning model. For instance, if the goal is to have a good balance, a threshold around 0.3 might be considered. If high precision is paramount, a threshold around 0.5 or higher could be chosen, accepting a lower recall.

QUICK OBSERVATIONAL SUMMARY INTERPRETATION This plot visualizes the trade-off between missing claims and over-flagging buildings. How to Read This Plot (Quick Orientation)

X-axis: Probability threshold

Y-axis: Score

Blue line = Recall (how many actual claims you catch)

Orange line = Precision (how many flagged buildings actually claim)

Red dashed line = Threshold = 0.3

Black dashed line = Threshold = 0.5

What the Plot Tells Us (Key Insights) Recall behavior (Blue line)

  • Very high recall at low thresholds (<0.2)
  • Sharp decline after ~0.25
  • At 0.5, recall is extremely low (~0.15) MEANING: At threshold 0.5, the model misses ~85% of actual claimsThis is unacceptable in insurance risk management.

The Precision behavior (Orange line)##

  • Precision increases steadily with threshold
  • Around 0.3, precision 0.45
  • At 0.5, precision 0.62 MEANING: Higher thresholds give cleaner predictions, but at the cost of missing claims.

Direct Comparison: 0.3 vs 0.5 (Critical)

Metric Threshold 0.3 Threshold 0.5
Recall 0.45 0.15 NOT GOOD
Precision 0.45 0.62
Missed claims Moderate Very High
Business risk Controlled Unacceptable
Underwriting value High Low

For insurance Logic:

  • False Negatives (missed claims) are far more costly than
  • False Positives (feasible for extra inspections)

Conclusive Explanation Precisionrecall analysis demonstrated that the default threshold of 0.5 resulted in unacceptably low recall, causing most claims to be missed. Lowering the threshold to approximately 0.3 provided a better balance between precision and recall, significantly increasing the proportion of detected claims while maintaining reasonable prediction accuracy. This threshold was therefore selected as the business-optimal decision point.

**Methodology **#

This project develops a data-driven insurance claim prediction model to support proactive risk identification. Using historical building, geographic, and protection-related features, a tuned Random Forest classifier was deployed to estimate claim probability. The model prioritizes minimizing missed claims by applying a calibrated decision threshold (0.30), accepting higher false positives in line with insurance risk management principles. The final solution is explainable, reproducible, and production ready.

1. Methodology 1.1 Data Understanding & Preservation

Original dataset preserved (df_raw) before transformations

Target variable: Claim (binary)

Class imbalance acknowledged (~23% claims)

1.2 Data Cleaning & Encoding

Binary categorical variables mapped to numeric values

High-cardinality geographic codes consolidated:

Geo codes with <50 observations grouped as OTHER

Reduced sparsity and improved generalization

One-hot encoding applied post-grouping

1.3 Feature Engineering

Log_Building_Dimension created to address strong right skew

Protection_Score engineered by combining correlated protection features

Outliers intentionally retained due to domain relevance (large buildings = higher risk)

1.4 Exploratory Data Analysis

Distribution plots and boxplots used for skew and outlier inspection

Correlation heatmap used to assess multicollinearity

3D plots used to visualize interaction between size, age, and claim risk

1.5 Modeling Strategy Baseline Model

Random Forest (300 trees)

ROC-AUC 0.70

Hyperparameter Tuning

RandomizedSearchCV (5-fold CV)

Optimized for ROC-AUC

Tuned model ROC-AUC 0.72

Benchmark Model

Logistic Regression with scaling and class balancing

ROC-AUC 0.70

1.6 Threshold Optimization

Default threshold (0.50) rejected

Business-aligned threshold 0.30 selected

Reduced false negatives at acceptable false positive cost

1.7 Model Explainability Permutation Importance was used for explainability Feature importance and PERMUTATION FEATURE IMPORTANCE used for explainability SHAPE SHAPE also explored Dominant drivers: Building Dimension, Log Dimension, Age, Windows

1.8 Model Persistence & Validation

Model, features, and threshold saved using joblib

Reload test confirmed reproducibility

  1. Final Model Decision
  • Tuned Random Forest selected * Threshold = 0.30

perm_importance = permutation_importance(
    model,
    X_test_aligned,
    y_test,
    n_repeats=10,
    random_state=42,
    scoring='roc_auc',
    n_jobs=-1
)

    'Importance': perm_importance.importances_mean

Non-Technical Final Executive Summary#

Executive Summary

This project develops a predictive machine learning model to estimate the probability that a building will experience at least one insurance claim during its insured period. The objective is to support proactive risk identification and informed decision-making by insurers, using building characteristics available at policy inception.

A structured data science workflow was followed, including data cleaning, feature engineering, exploratory analysis, model training, evaluation, explainability, and validation. Special care was taken to ensure the model aligns with real-world insurance logic and remains interpretable and defensible.

The final model selected is a tuned Random Forest classifier, optimized using cross-validated ROC-AUC. Compared with a benchmark logistic regression model, the Random Forest demonstrated superior discriminatory power while capturing nonlinear risk patterns inherent in building data. Model performance achieved an ROC-AUC of approximately 0.72, indicating reliable separation between claim and non-claim buildings.

Rather than relying on the default probability threshold of 0.50, a business-aligned threshold of 0.30 was selected. This decision prioritizes the reduction of missed claims (false negatives), accepting a controlled increase in false positives. This trade-off is appropriate in insurance contexts where early identification of high-risk buildings is more valuable than strict precision.

Feature explainability was addressed using permutation feature importance, which revealed that claim risk is driven primarily by exposure-related variables, notably building size and insured duration. Structural attributes such as number of windows and building type act as secondary risk modifiers, while geographic and protection features provide contextual refinement without dominating predictions. This behavior is consistent with domain expectations and supports trust in the model.

To ensure reproducibility and deployment readiness, the final trained model, feature schema, and decision threshold were persisted using industry-standard tools. Reload testing confirmed consistent predictions across sessions.

In conclusion, the developed model is robust, interpretable, and aligned with insurance business objectives. It is suitable for deployment in claim risk flagging systems and can be periodically recalibrated as claim patterns evolve.
